John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent track record in academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for advanced and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “When you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t only rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest pass rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 percent of students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students German, 69 percent of students French and 63 percent of students Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of the obstacles to filling out vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job vacancies requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, in the future he will have a real advantage with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that stood above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today’s children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
Schools in Scotland choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied at the moment that languages remain vital to the future of the country in a global business environment, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It is very fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
