North Korea Says It Will ‘Never Unilaterally Disarm Without Confidence’
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions are leading to increasing distrust in the United States and that under such circumstances the country could under no circumstances give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as cessation of nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the site for nuclear tests, and the promise not to distribute nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any confidence in the US, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances, we will not unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, rewarding North Korea as it moves forward, it noted that he did not a priori disapprove of unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang once did.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work toward the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is aiming for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war,’ Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an air castle of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only reinforce our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the U.S. leader suggested at the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister instead emphasized three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a deadlock.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles should be targeted on the U.S. mainland after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, praised Kim at the United Nations this year for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said there is still much to be done and that the sanctions must continue until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable: “Whether it’s two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must be continued vigorously and firmly until we have achieved the complete, definitive, verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously sanctioned North Korea to significantly reduce funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea promised during a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States were to take “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he wanted were security guarantees that Trump had pledged in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night while drinking a lot of caffeine.
One professor found that the students of the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basics to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course. As far as he knows, it is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech about the influence of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why can’t I hear this until my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is organized for the first time this year, explains to the students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was found that students had severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we think they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what impact cigarettes have on their health, Czeisler added.
Continuing the culture of pride on a night-time basis still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course, after all, he had taken lessons with the professor last year when he was studying at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before they come to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, not just an alarm to get up. They also need to be aware of the damaging effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, which can make you have trouble falling asleep.
