The inventor of the World Wide Web plans a new internet to tackle Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, starts a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the technology legend’s latest project, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that “world domination” is the guiding thought behind Inrupt.
“We have to do this now,” he said of the start-up.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to enable people to create their own “personal online data storage” or POD.
It can store lists of contacts, activity lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together through one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is the fact that it completely depends on the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea behind Inrupt, according to CEO John Bruce, is that the company provides the resources, processes and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not going to have conversations with “Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete transformation that will completely upset all their business models at once.”
“We don’t ask for their permission.”
In a post on Medium published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that the “mission [of Inrupt] is to deliver the commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
After the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this new era for the web,” Berners-Lee added.
