Lieutenant-Colonel, Reverend Bernard Vann received the award following the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt on September 29, 1918.
However, he was killed four days later by a sniper and thus never knew that he had received the highest British military honor.
A memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandsons during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of the grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was “brilliantly symbolic” that the stone was revealed exactly 100 years after the fact for which his grandfather had been distinguished.
According to the London Gazette, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under fierce fire of field guns and machine guns" on September 29, 1918.
He later stormed to the line of fire and led the line forward before running alone to a field gun and shutting down three members of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I can never touch, but also something that makes me feel humble.”
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
