How the U.S.-China Trade War Can Benefit Beijing
The opening salvos of the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and although the battle is far from over, a gap between the two countries could, according to experts, be beneficial for Beijing in the long run.
US President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by raising taxes on major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation was announced this week when new effective, increased tax rates were unveiled for 200 billion dollars (150 billion euros) of goods; half of all goods coming from China to the US.
Beijing has taken reprisals in kind every time, most recently by raising rates from 5 to 10% for $60 billion in U.S. goods.
China has pledged to match the US every time, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to blink quickly.
In order for Washington to bow, requests must be granted, but publicly bowing to the US is far too painful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts argue that if Beijing plays it smart, the trade war with the US could positively support China in the longer term, as the reciprocal dependence of the two economies decreases.
“The fact that a swift political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that could put either country in economic freefall is actually far more dangerous than spectators have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, a research associate at the Center for a New American Security, a think tank specializing in national security issues that focuses on Asia.
Syria 'ready' to return refugees, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country destroyed by a war lasting more than seven years.
During his speech to the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that conditions in his country were improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas that have been destroyed by terrorists, and to normalize the situation on the spot.
All conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that threatened their daily lives and existence.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled their country since the war began in 2011.
It is estimated that there are still about six million people in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome help in restoring the devastated country.
However, he stressed that Syria would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from countries that had subsidized the uprising.
