Red glow update: Concentrations are decreasing in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decrease in red glow concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the commission, it is reported that there is a fragmentary increase in the red glow in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots to see, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow has also been seen in Pasco County.
There have been medium concentrations reported off the coast of Pinellas County last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are ongoing reports of respiratory irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no respiratory irritation has been reported in the past week.
